punditry: [BEL] lead by 258 points heading into the final match.

1962/63.punditry: The league's inaugural season, founded at The Three Kings pub in Mitcham. Walton AC became the first champions with solid packing throughout. Gerry North (Belgrave) won 3 of 4 races but Bob Roath (Walton) took the individual title.

1963/64.punditry: Belgrave fielded 50 runners in Race 1 and took an early lead, but Walton fought back to retain the title. Bob Roath won his second consecutive individual championship.

1964/65.punditry: Croydon joined as the 7th team. Walton's hat-trick hopes ended when they couldn't field a complete team in Race 2. Hercules capitalised on a weak Belgrave Race 3 showing to take their first title. Tokyo Olympic 5000m runner Bengt Nadje (Sweden) became the league's first overseas race winner.

1965/66.punditry: Gerry and Geoff North returned from training in Mexico to lead Belgrave to their first title. Race 3 saw a rare team tie between Belgrave and Mitcham (both 255 pts). The final race gave Belgrave their clearest margin yet.

1966/67.punditry: First season with promotion/relegation as Mid-Surrey League became Division 2. Belgrave started poorly (4th in Race 1) but stormed back. Gerry North and Bob Holt ran home together in the final race. Herne Hill were relegated after finishing bottom.

1967/68.punditry: Race 2 was cancelled due to a blizzard - the season completed with only 3 races. A hat-trick of titles for Belgrave with Gerry North's 9.5 point margin over Bob Holt. Surrey AC finished bottom and were relegated - the club's men's section would later merge into Belgrave.

1968/69.punditry: Hercules AC and Wimbledon AC merged to form Hercules Wimbledon AC. Belgrave won all 4 races for the first time in league history, extending their dominance to 4 consecutive titles.

1969/70.punditry: South London finally joined Division 1 after initially declining a place in 1962. Race 3 saw the Holt brothers (Bob and Dave) dead-heat for the win - their combined 3 points remains the all-time record for brothers. Belgrave made it 5 titles in a row.

1970/71.punditry: Belgrave's 6th consecutive title came despite less dominance at the front of races. Founder members Walton AC were relegated. Aldershot F&D won Division 2 and would shake up the established order.

1971/72.punditry: Newly promoted Aldershot F&D won Race 2, showing the form that would see them challenge for titles. Belgrave secured a 7th successive crown, boosted by talented U20s Pete Carton, John Stow, Tony Binda and Bill Curtin. Mitcham AC were relegated and would subsequently merge with Sutton & Cheam to form Sutton & District AC.

1976/77.punditry: Belgrave finished bottom and were relegated from Division 1 for the first time in league history. The founding member's fall from grace came after a seven-season winning streak ended in 1973, precipitating a steady decline before this season's relegation.

1990/91.note: Match 4 at Coulsdon cancelled due to snow
